<article>
    <h1>Boost your men&#xAD;tal health</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200907/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-07"><time>2020-09-07</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE MIND &amp; BODY</span>
        - <span role="byline">This ar&#xAD;ti&#xAD;cle pro&#xAD;vides gen&#xAD;eral in&#xAD;for&#xAD;ma&#xAD;tion only and is not a sub&#xAD;sti&#xAD;tute for med&#xAD;i&#xAD;cal ad&#xAD;vice. Please con&#xAD;sult med&#xAD;i&#xAD;cal or health&#xAD;care pro&#xAD;fes&#xAD;sion&#xAD;als for ad&#xAD;vice on health- r elated mat&#xAD;ters.</span>
    </section>

    <p>With meet­ings and dead­lines to jug­gle in our ‘al­ways-on’ cul­ture, it’s im­por­tant to dis­con­nect and make time for your­self. Fol­low these sim­ple tips to im­prove your men­tal well-be­ing for a health­ier, hap­pier you.</p>
    <p>Keep a grat­i­tude jour­nal</p>
    <p>Grat­i­tude is linked to im­proved well-be­ing and in­creased lev­els of hap­pi­ness. Think about what you are grate­ful for and elab­o­rate on why you feel grat­i­tude for a par­tic­u­lar thing. Re­flect­ing on such events helps you pay at­ten­tion to things you might oth­er­wise take for granted.</p>
    <p>Ex­er­cise reg­u­larly</p>
    <p>Ex­er­cise un­leashes en­dor­phins, feel-good chem­i­cals that lift your mood, and low­ers de­pres­sion and anx­i­ety. Aim to ac­com­plish at least 30 min­utes of ex­er­cise a day.</p>
    <p>Make an ef­fort to wake up early to hit the gym be­fore work. You’ll be more en­er­getic and ready to tackle the day ahead. Af­ter work, de­stress with a brisk walk or jog around your neigh­bour­hood. Go cycling or visit the park on week­ends. Breathe in the fresh air and en­joy the great out­doors – it's been proven that be­ing in na­ture re­duces stress.</p>
    <p>Eat right</p>
    <p>What you put in your body af­fects how you feel. Drink plenty of wa­ter, cut down on su­gar, sodium and fat, and eat more fruit and veg­eta­bles. This might seem like com­mon sense, but it’s easy to de­velop poor eat­ing habits when you let stress get the bet­ter of you. Start your day with a whole­some break­fast of whole­meal bread or ce­real, and break up your meals for the rest of the day so you don’t overeat.</p>
    <p>Take a break</p>
    <p>When things get over­whelm­ing, step back and do some­thing to take your mind off what­ever is stress­ing you out. Try this sim­ple breath­ing ex­er­cise: close your eyes and take 10 deep breaths. For each breath, count to four as you in­hale, hold it for a count of four, then ex­hale for an­other four counts. This should calm you down im­me­di­ately.</p>
    <p>Fo­cus on your re­la­tion­ships</p>
    <p>Stud­ies have shown that peo­ple with strong fam­ily and so­cial bonds are health­ier than those with­out a sup­port net­work. Have reg­u­lar fam­ily gath­er­ings, make plans with friends and join in­ter­est groups to meet like-minded peo­ple. Put your phone aside when you’re with oth­ers and fully en­gage in the con­ver­sa­tion and your sur­round­ings. Spend time with the peo­ple who mat­ter to you; work will al­ways be there but your loved ones won’t.</p>

